\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Actualism}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 geology - actualism.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Actualism}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in geology is the idea that the facts of geology can and should be explained in terms of the sort of physical processes that actually happen.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 As such, it can be considered both as a scientific theory (that the facts\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 can}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~be explained by real processes) and as a methodological principle (that they\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 should}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~be so explained).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 You might wonder why there is a need to have a name for this. You might also wonder why it is necessary to mention it particularly in a textbook on geology, since after all this is a universal scientific principle. Chemists (to take one example) are just as much actualists as geologists, because all scientists are; and yet they do not include a section on actualism in their textbooks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The reason why it is mentioned particularly in geological textbooks is a historical one. For many centuries people have been trying to explain geology in terms of non-actual, magical processes: explaining, for example, that the Earth's strata were produced by God turning off the force of gravity and then turning it back on; or that God created fossils when he made the Earth so that coal-miners even when underground would have visible signs of his presence. Various religious sects still promote non-actual concepts of geology to this present day.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 As we have said, actualism (considered as the assertion that the geological record\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 can}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~be explained in terms of real processes) should be regarded as a scientific theory. Why? \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  because it is testable. We can look at the rocks, and we would recognize if there was something in the geological record which could not be explained in terms of real processes.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 In fact, as you will recall from previous articles, what we find is that we can explain what we see: we can explain\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Till"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 glacial till}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in terms of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Glaciers"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 glaciers}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , marine\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Limestone"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 limestone}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in terms of the deposition of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Calcareous_ooze"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 calcareous ooze}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Chemical_weathering"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 chemical weathering}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in terms of chemistry,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Paleomagnetism"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 paleomagnetism}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in terms of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Continental_drift"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 continental drift}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Saline_giant"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 saline giants}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~in terms of the evaporation of seawater, and so forth.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 If there are still things that are not yet perfectly explained, such as the question of how\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 exactly}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Glacier"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 glaciers}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~make\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Drumlin"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 drumlins}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , then we can hardly regard that as a falsification of the\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Theory"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 theory}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , but merely an area in which more work needs to be done, for it is not plain that\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Drumlin"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 drumlins}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 cannot}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~be explained by a better understanding of actual\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Glacial"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 glacial}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~processes and would instead require the invocation of a non-actualistic being such as the Drumlin Fairy to fill this minor gap in our knowledge.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 If, on the other hand (for example) we split open two leaves of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Slate"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 slate}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~and found therein the first chapter of Genesis written in\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Historical_Geology/Glossary_and_index#Quartz"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 quartz}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , then this would falsify actualism; we could not even imagine that one day we would find any ordinary physical process that would explain the phenomenon: we know too much about the way in which the world works to consider that even for a moment.}
